A closure is a function that retains access to variables from its parent function even after the parent function has finished executing. Here's an example:

```
function outer() {
  var x = 10;
  function inner() {
    console.log(x);
  }
  return inner;
}

var closure = outer();
closure(); // Outputs 10
```
In this example, 'inner' is a closure that can access the 'x' variable even though 'outer' has finished executing.

